{
  "text": "The PWWP domain was first described as a structural motif in WHSC1, a HKMT involved in the Wolf-Hirschhorn syndrome [CITATION_1] . The Pro-Trp-Trp-Pro sequence motif is conserved in eukaryotes and the protein domains that encompass it usually contain about 90-130 amino acids. Despite conservation, some variations on the Pro-Trp-Trp-Pro sequence motif may occur. For example, the PWWP domains of the DNA methyltransferases DNMT3a/b contain SWWP motifs [CITATION_2] , while that of the hepatoma-derived growth factor (HDGF) comprises a PHWP motif [CITATION_3] (Fig. 1) . Recently, the first position of the Pro-Trp-TrpPro sequence motif has been shown to regulate the PWWP domain stability and oligomerization [CITATION_4] . PWWP domains that contain a proline as the first amino acid residue of the Pro-Trp-Trp-Pro motif are more stable, less dynamic, and less prone to aggregation than those that display an alanine at the same position [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "18497879",
